[This is an interesting discussion of a very practical matter and we
appreciate Dr. Eidson's taking time to send her thoughts and data to us. A
plague expert, to whom I am grateful, at CDC/Ft. Collins suggested to me
that flea control is recommended primarily to reduce the risk that hunting
cats will bring infectious fleas into their owners' homes, rather than as a
means to keep cats from getting plague. As Dr. Eidson points out, most
cats appear to acquire plague through ingesting infected rodents (these
conclusions come largely from studies she published in the Am J Vet Med).
Nevertheless, cats that explore rodent burrows, or kill and eat
flea-infested rodents, could serve as temporary hosts for these
ectoparasites and bring them into human habitations, etc., where they could
jump off and bite people - Mod CHC]
